As Dawn first spread her yellow robe across the earth,\uc0\u8232 thunder-loving Zeus summoned an assembly of the gods\u8232 on the highest crest of many-ridged Olympus.\u8232 Zeus himself addressed them. The other deities,\u8232 those ranked below him, listened carefully.\
\'a0\'93Hear me, all you gods and goddesses,\uc0\u8232 I\'92ll speak what the spirit in my chest prompts.\u8232 And let no female god, no male one either,\u8232 seek to thwart my plan. Let\'92s get agreement\u8232 from all of you to end this matter quickly.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a010\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[10]\u8232 If I see any of you breaking ranks of gods,\u8232 keen to assist the Trojans or Danaans,\u8232 that god I\'92ll beat up ignominiously\u8232 and send back to Olympus. Or I\'92ll seize him\u8232 and pitch him into black Tartarus, way down,\u8232 into the deepest pit below the earth,\u8232 where the gates are iron, the threshold bronze,\u8232 as far below Hades as heaven lies\u8232 above the earth. Then he\'92ll acknowledge\u8232 just how strong I am, the strongest of all gods.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a020\u8232 Come on, try it\'97then everyone will know.\u8232 Take a golden cord, hang it from heaven.\u8232 Let gods and goddesses, all together,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[20]\u8232 grab hold of one end of it and pull.\u8232 You\'92d not drag Zeus, the highest counsellor,\u8232 down from heaven to the ground, never,\u8232 no matter how hard you tried to do it.\u8232 But when I wished to pull in earnest,\u8232 I\'92d yank up earth itself, the sea as well.\u8232 I\'92d loop that cord round some Olympian peak\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a030\u8232 and hang it in mid-air\'97the whole of it.\u8232 I\'92m that much stronger than the gods and men.\'94\
Zeus finished. All the gods were speechless, shocked\uc0\u8232 at what Zeus had said, at the power of his tone.\u8232 At last Athena, the bright-eyed goddess, spoke up:\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[30]\
\'93Son of Cronos, you\'92re the father of us all,\uc0\u8232 highest ruling force. We well know your strength.\u8232 It\'92s invincible. Still, we\'92re sorry for the troops,\u8232 Danaan spearmen dying, suffering dreadful fates.\u8232 But we\'92ll stand apart from battle, as you wish,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a040\u8232 although we\'92ll give the Argives our advice,\u8232 help them, to prevent destruction of them all,\u8232 just to answer your displeasure.\'94\
Cloud-gatherer Zeus, smiling at Athena, said:\
\'93My dear child Tritogeneia, have no fears.\uc0\u8232 I wasn\'92t speaking all that seriously.\u8232 I want to treat you in a friendly way.\'94\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[40]\
Zeus harnessed his two horses, swift-flying animals,\uc0\u8232 with hooves of bronze and flowing golden manes.\u8232 He encased his body all in gold, took up his whip,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a050\u8232 a gold one, finely crafted, climbed in his chariot,\u8232 then lashed the horses onward. They flew off eagerly.\u8232 Midway between the earth and starry heaven,\u8232 Zeus reached Mount Ida with its many springs,\u8232 mother of wild beasts. He reached Gargaros,\u8232 site of his grove and temple, fragrant with sacrifice.\u8232 There, the father of gods and men reined in his horses,\u8232 untied them from the chariot, and hid them in thick cloud.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[50]\u8232 Then he sat on the mountain peak, proud and splendid,\u8232 gazing down on the Trojan city, the Achaean ships.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a060\
Long-haired Achaeans gulped a quick meal by their huts.\uc0\u8232 Then they armed themselves. On the other side, in town,\u8232 Trojans, too, prepared for war, fewer in number,\u8232 but keen to fight on in the killing zone, a grim necessity,\u8232 for wives and children. They threw open all the gates.\u8232 The army streamed out, foot soldiers and charioteers,\u8232 making a huge din. As the two groups moved out\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[60]\u8232 to the same spot, they crashed together, smashing shields\u8232 and spears, the battle frenzy of bronze-armed warriors.\u8232 Embossed shields collided one against the other,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a070\u8232 a tremendous noise. Screams of pain and triumph\u8232 came from soldiers\'97those killing, those being killed\'97\u8232 and the earth was saturated with their blood.\
In early morning, as that sacred day grew stronger,\uc0\u8232 weapons hurled by both sides grimly took their toll\'97\u8232 men kept on dying. But when the sun was at its height,\u8232 Father Zeus set up his golden balance, placed on it\u8232 two fatal destinies, one for horse-taming Trojans,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[70]\u8232 one for bronze-armed Achaeans. Gripping the scales,\u8232 he raised them by the centre. One scale sank down,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a080\u8232 the one which held the Achaeans\'92 fate that day\'97\u8232 it moved down towards the all-sustaining earth,\u8232 while the Trojans\'92 fate rose up toward wide heaven.\u8232 From Mount Ida, Zeus sent out a loud thunder clap\u8232 and hurled a lighting bolt down on Achaean troops.\u8232 Men looked and were astounded. Pale fear gripped them all.\u8232 At that, Idomeneus did not dare to stand his ground,\u8232 nor did Agamemnon, nor the two men named Ajax,\u8232 companions of the war god Ares. Only Nestor,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[80]\u8232 the Geranian, guardian of Achaeans,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a090\u8232 kept his place, but not because he wanted to.\u8232 One of his horses had been hurt, hit by an arrow\u8232 on its head, right on top, that spot where on a horse\u8232 hairs start to grow out from the skull, a deadly place.\u8232 The arrow had been loosed by Alexander,\u8232 lovely Helen\'92s mate. The beast reared up in agony,\u8232 as the arrow pierced its brain. Skewered by the shaft,\u8232 the beast\'92s convulsions confused the other horses.\u8232 While old Nestor with his sword was hacking feverishly\u8232 to cut the traces holding the animal in place,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0100\u8232 Hector\'92s fast horses came through the fighting men,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[90]\u8232 bearing Hector with them and their bold charioteer.\u8232 Nestor would have died right there, if Diomedes,\u8232 skilled in war cries, hadn\'92t seen him right away.\u8232 He let out a loud shout to Odysseus, urging him\u8232 to come to Nestor\'92s help.\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93Noble Odysseus, Laertes\'92 son,\uc0\u8232 you resourceful man, why move away,\u8232 turning your back on all these flying weapons,\u8232 like a coward? Watch someone doesn\'92t spear you\u8232 right in the back as you run off. Come on,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0110\u8232 let\'92s save old man Nestor from wild Hector.\'94\
Diomedes\'92 words missed godlike, firm Odysseus,\uc0\u8232 who moved off to the Achaeans\'92 hollow ships.\u8232 Diomedes, though left alone, charged straight ahead,\u8232 back into the fight. He made a stand right there,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[100]\u8232 in front of old Nestor\'92s chariot, calling out to Nestor,\u8232 son of Neleus\'97his words had wings.\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93Old man, in this fight\uc0\u8232 these young men are pressing you too hard.\u8232 Your strength is waning. Old age weighs you down.\u8232 Your attendant\'92s weak, your horses slow.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0120\u8232 So come on, climb up into my chariot.\u8232 You\'92ll see how these Trojan horses do,\u8232 experts in moving to and fro across the plain,\u8232 in pursuit or flight. I took them from Aeneas.\u8232 These horses would fill any man with terror.\u8232 So turn your team over to subordinates.\u8232 With my two let\'92s charge against the Trojans.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[110]\u8232 Let Hector see how my hand wields a spear.\'94\
Geranian horseman Nestor followed this suggestion.\uc0\u8232 At once, the two strong officers, Sthelenus\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0130\u8232 and noble Eurymedon, took Nestor\'92s horses.\u8232 The two men climbed up in Diomedes\'92 chariot.\u8232 Nestor grabbed the shining reins and lashed the horses.\u8232 They closed in on Hector quickly. Then he, in turn,\u8232 eager to fight, charged them impetuously.\u8232 The son of Tydeus threw his spear at Hector.\u8232 He missed, but struck Hector\'92s companion charioteer,\u8232 Eniopeus, son of proud Thebaios, in the chest,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[120]\u8232 right by the nipple, as Eniopeus held the reins.\u8232 He tumbled from the chariot. The swift horses swerved.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0140\u8232 Then strength and spirit left him as he lay there.\u8232 Savage grief seized Hector for his charioteer,\u8232 but he left him lying there, for all the pain he felt\u8232 for his companion. He went to find a substitute,\u8232 a second driver full of courage. Before long,\u8232 those horses had another charioteer,\u8232 for Hector soon ran into Archeptolemos,\u8232 son of Iphitus, and placed him in the chariot\u8232 behind swift horses, then handed him the reins.\
At that point irrevocable disaster might have struck\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0150\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[130]\uc0\u8232 the people all penned up in Troy like sheep,\u8232 if the father of gods and men hadn\'92t kept sharp watch.\u8232 Sounding a dreadful thunder clap, he loosed his lightning,\u8232 a dazzling fiery bolt which hit the ground\u8232 immediately in front of Diomedes\'92 horses.\u8232 A dreadful flash came from the blazing sulphur.\u8232 In terror, both horses reared up in their harnesses.\u8232 Nestor let the shining reins drop from his hands.\u8232 Feeling fear inside his chest, he cried:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93Son of Tydeus,\uc0\u8232 wheel your sure-footed horses round. Go back.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0160\u8232 Don\'92t you see Zeus is not protecting you?\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[140]\u8232 Today the son of Cronos grants Hector glory.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\u8232 Tomorrow he\'92ll give victory to us,\u8232 if that\'92s his will. No man stops Zeus\'92 plans,\u8232 no one, not even the mightiest warrior.\u8232 Zeus\'92 force is more powerful by far.\'94\
Diomedes, expert in war cries, then replied:\
\'93Everything you say, old man, is true enough.\uc0\u8232 But this brings fearful pain into my heart and chest.\u8232 For Hector then will speak out in Troy.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0170\u8232 He\'92ll say,\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'91The son of Tydeus, in fear of me,\uc0\u8232 scurried off, back to his ships.\'92\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0That\'92s what he\'92ll boast.\uc0\u8232 Then let the wide earth open up for me.\'94\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[150]\
Geranian horseman Nestor answered Diomedes:\
\'93Son of fiery-hearted Tydeus, why talk like that?\uc0\u8232 Even if he slanders you and calls you coward,\u8232 he\'92ll not convince the Trojans or Dardanians,\u8232 or Trojan wives, married partners of brave men\u8232 you\'92ve thrown into the dirt, still in their prime.\'94\
With these words he turned the sure-footed horses back,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0180\uc0\u8232 fleeing through the battle zone. Hector and the Trojans,\u8232 with a shout, threw volleys of lethal weapons at them.\u8232 Hector with his glittering helmet then yelled out:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93Son of Tydeus,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[160]\uc0\u8232 fast-riding Danaans at their banquets\u8232 have awarded you a place of honour,\u8232 with lots of meat, a wine cup always full.\u8232 Now they\'92re ashamed of you. You\'92ve turned out\u8232 no better than a woman. Run off then,\u8232 you coward girl. I\'92ll not back away,\u8232 let you climb our walls, or take our women.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0190\u8232 Before that happens, I\'92ll send you to your death.\'94\
