\'93You Argives! What a shameful bunch of men!\uc0\u8232 Splendid to look at, but a sour disgrace!\u8232 What\'92s happened to our sworn oaths, when we claimed\u8232 we were the best, the bravest? Idle boasters!\u8232 In Lemnos, as you stuffed yourselves with meat\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0270\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[230]\u8232 from straight-horned cattle and drank bowls of wine,\u8232 foaming to the brim, you talked of how you\'92d stand,\u8232 each and every one of you, firm in battle\u8232 against a hundred or two hundred Trojans.\u8232 Now we\'92re matched by Hector, just one man,\u8232 who\'92ll quickly set our ships alight with fire.\u8232 Father Zeus, have you ever so deluded\u8232 a high-minded king and stolen his glory?\u8232 While sailing well-decked ships to this disaster,\u8232 I say I never overlooked your lovely altars.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0280\u8232 On every one I burned fat and thighs of oxen\'97\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[240]\u8232 I was so keen to conquer Troy, its well-made walls.\u8232 But Zeus, grant me now at least this prayer\'97\u8232 let us get out of here alive, in safety.\u8232 Don\'92t let Trojans kill Achaeans off like this.\'94\
